WEBVTT

00:06.840 --> 00:09.760
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.760 --> 00:11.845
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:11.845 --> 00:15.807
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:15.807 --> 00:19.061
<i>- My name is Alan Kirby, and my</i>
<i>forge is Coconut Empire Forge.</i>

00:19.061 --> 00:21.396
I've done ceramics
for 17 years.

00:21.396 --> 00:25.317
<i>When I found that clay</i>
<i>and steel move very similarly,</i>

00:25.317 --> 00:27.736
I knew I found my passion.

00:27.736 --> 00:30.739
<i>- Name's Hunter Johnson. I'm</i>
<i>from Philippi, West Virginia.</i>

00:30.739 --> 00:33.700
My actual day job, I manage
a fast-food restaurant.

00:33.700 --> 00:34.910
<i>I've been bladesmithing</i>
<i>part-time</i>

00:34.910 --> 00:36.787
<i>for about 2 1/2 years now,</i>

00:36.787 --> 00:38.872
<i>and I'd love to be able</i>
<i>to do this full-time.</i>

00:38.872 --> 00:41.416
I do not want to smell
another French fry in my life.

00:41.416 --> 00:44.753
<i>- I'm Edward Lacey.</i>
<i>I broke my back in '99.</i>

00:44.753 --> 00:46.797
<i>I was no good to anybody.</i>

00:46.797 --> 00:49.174
I was this close
to eating a bullet.

00:49.174 --> 00:51.343
<i>Knife making gave me purpose,</i>

00:51.343 --> 00:53.929
saved my life,
I guess you could say.

00:53.929 --> 00:55.555
<i>- My name's Tim Lough.</i>

00:55.555 --> 00:57.766
I'm definitely a weapons
and armor nerd,

00:57.766 --> 00:59.977
possibly bordering on geek.

00:59.977 --> 01:03.146
<i>Metal is a medicine for me.</i>

01:03.146 --> 01:05.274
My wife'll tell me--if
she'll see me getting

01:05.274 --> 01:06.733
<i>antsed up about something,</i>
<i>and she'll tell me,</i>

01:06.733 --> 01:09.069
"Just go to your shop."

01:09.069 --> 01:12.072
- Bladesmiths, welcome
to the Forge.

01:12.072 --> 01:14.908
Each of you has volunteered
to engage in three timed

01:14.908 --> 01:17.202
rounds of edged
weapon-making competition

01:17.202 --> 01:19.079
specifically designed

01:19.079 --> 01:21.331
to put every aspect
of your skills to the test,

01:21.331 --> 01:23.083
and of course,
at the end of each round,

01:23.083 --> 01:26.753
inspecting your work
is our panel of expert judges,

01:26.753 --> 01:28.130
two-time "Forged
in Fire" champion

01:28.130 --> 01:30.257
and fan favorite Ben Abbott,

01:30.257 --> 01:32.217
next, historic weapons
re-creation specialist

01:32.217 --> 01:34.636
David Baker,

01:34.636 --> 01:37.180
and Kali martial artist
Doug Marcaida.

01:37.180 --> 01:39.558
These are the men who decide
which of you will be

01:39.558 --> 01:40.976
our next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:40.976 --> 01:43.520
and win that check
for 10 grand.

01:43.520 --> 01:45.522
All right, gentlemen,

01:45.522 --> 01:49.318
today you will be competing
in our San Mai challenge,

01:49.318 --> 01:54.614
so on your anvils is a cloth.
Go ahead and lift that up.

01:54.614 --> 01:56.825
Those are high-carbon drill
bits,

01:56.825 --> 02:00.370
<i>and there's a soft steel</i>
<i>billet inside that box.</i>

02:00.370 --> 02:03.165
The San Mai challenge
is forging blades

02:03.165 --> 02:06.585
<i>in your signature style</i>
<i>by sandwiching soft steel</i>

02:06.585 --> 02:12.341
<i>around a hardenable</i>
<i>steel core and edge.</i>

02:12.341 --> 02:15.427
<i>- I am in so much trouble</i>
<i>right now.</i>

02:15.427 --> 02:18.680
<i>I have never, ever messed</i>
<i>with the drill bits.</i>

02:18.680 --> 02:20.891
<i>Just getting those</i>
<i>straightened out</i>

02:20.891 --> 02:23.602
and getting them into a billet
is gonna be a challenge enough.

02:23.602 --> 02:25.395
<i>I'm in trouble.</i>

02:25.395 --> 02:27.105
- Keep in mind that
in the second round

02:27.105 --> 02:28.774
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

02:28.774 --> 02:30.692
to turn them into fully
functional weapons

02:30.692 --> 02:33.362
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:33.362 --> 02:36.365
in a coconut chop
and for edge retention

02:36.365 --> 02:39.076
in a ratchet strap slice.

02:39.076 --> 02:40.869
You will have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

02:40.869 --> 02:43.038
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:43.038 --> 02:45.874
Keep an eye on the clock
because when the time runs out

02:45.874 --> 02:48.126
and the judges have
inspected your work,

02:48.126 --> 02:50.045
one of you will be asked
to surrender your blade

02:50.045 --> 02:51.672
and leave the Forge.

02:51.672 --> 02:53.423
All right, bladesmiths,
grab your steel.

02:53.423 --> 02:56.426
Your ten-minute
design window starts now.

02:56.426 --> 03:03.642
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:03.642 --> 03:06.103
I think we've noticed that
smiths will show up here,

03:06.103 --> 03:08.188
and they'll make
a thick, heavy blade,

03:08.188 --> 03:10.148
and it won't do as well
on the sharpness test.

03:10.148 --> 03:12.609
How do they rectify
that problem?

03:12.609 --> 03:14.361
- They have to
trust their steel.

03:14.361 --> 03:15.737
It doesn't have to be
big and fat and clunky

03:15.737 --> 03:17.364
to survive a coconut chop.

03:17.364 --> 03:19.199
<i>- I was very excited to learn</i>

03:19.199 --> 03:21.576
<i>that the challenge</i>
<i>is a coconut chop</i>

03:21.576 --> 03:23.328
<i>'cause it fits right</i>
<i>with the name of my forge,</i>

03:23.328 --> 03:25.330
Coconut Empire Forge.

03:25.330 --> 03:27.332
It might have been fate.

03:27.332 --> 03:28.458
<i>A chef's knife would</i>
<i>probably be the best thing</i>

03:28.458 --> 03:30.752
<i>to prepare that coconut.</i>

03:30.752 --> 03:33.672
<i>It's also sharp to do tomatoes</i>
<i>or even a ratchet strap slice.</i>

03:33.672 --> 03:35.424
That's gonna be
my weapon of choice.

03:35.424 --> 03:37.634
- That gives us enough room.

03:37.634 --> 03:40.679
I'm gonna go to my standard
go-to blade, which is a seax.

03:40.679 --> 03:42.931
<i>As far as chopping, it's gonna</i>
<i>have some weight to it,</i>

03:42.931 --> 03:45.308
<i>and as far as slicing,</i>
<i>if I put the right edge to it,</i>

03:45.308 --> 03:48.019
<i>the right angle on it,</i>
<i>she'll slice just great.</i>

03:48.019 --> 03:49.896
<i>I am a self-trained bladesmith.</i>

03:49.896 --> 03:53.984
If I can win, if it proves
anything to anybody,

03:53.984 --> 03:55.819
<i>it's gonna be proving</i>
<i>something to me,</i>

03:55.819 --> 03:58.572
<i>that I could do</i>
<i>championship bladesmithing.</i>

03:58.572 --> 04:00.699
- Two minutes, bladesmiths.

04:00.699 --> 04:02.701
<i>- I sketched out</i>
<i>three different designs</i>

04:02.701 --> 04:04.953
<i>because I wanted to make sure</i>
<i>that I was gonna like it</i>

04:04.953 --> 04:06.830
<i>and think</i>
<i>that it was gonna work,</i>

04:06.830 --> 04:08.290
just kind of picked the one
that I thought was closest

04:08.290 --> 04:10.375
to what would work
for the challenge,

04:10.375 --> 04:13.044
<i>so my best bet, I'm thinking,</i>
<i>is some kind of chopper,</i>

04:13.044 --> 04:15.255
<i>something of that shape that's</i>
<i>gonna handle that coconut</i>

04:15.255 --> 04:19.259
and still be able to cut.

04:19.259 --> 04:21.511
- I'm designing a kukri-style
blade.

04:21.511 --> 04:24.681
<i>The kukri offers</i>
<i>a nice belly sweet spot</i>

04:24.681 --> 04:28.101
<i>to actually strike</i>
<i>and hang onto an object.</i>

04:28.101 --> 04:29.853
- We have air chopping.

04:29.853 --> 04:31.688
- Air chopping in
the design period.

04:31.688 --> 04:34.024
- That's a first.
- Dang. Boy, that's a record.

04:34.024 --> 04:35.859
- You got to imagine where
your hand's gonna go.

04:35.859 --> 04:40.947
- Five, four, three, two, one.

04:40.947 --> 04:43.450
Bladesmiths, the design
period is closed.

04:43.450 --> 04:46.411
Your three-hour forge
times starts now.

04:46.411 --> 04:52.834
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:52.834 --> 04:55.670
- Eeny, meeny, miney, right?
- Yeah.

04:55.670 --> 04:58.048
- So these boxes have a large
chunk of mild steel in them

04:58.048 --> 05:01.885
as well as all of those
high-carbon bits,

05:01.885 --> 05:04.262
but those bits are not
a uniform shape.

05:04.262 --> 05:06.556
How are they supposed
to forge-weld them down?

05:06.556 --> 05:08.683
- I'd unscrew them,
flatten that out,

05:08.683 --> 05:11.061
and then San Mai that.

05:11.061 --> 05:12.604
<i>- Yeah, it's gonna be tricky</i>
<i>working with these drill bits.</i>

05:12.604 --> 05:14.272
<i>I mean, they're such</i>
<i>an odd shape.</i>

05:14.272 --> 05:16.441
If you try to just
forge them flat-out,

05:16.441 --> 05:18.235
you might have cold shuts where
they're not gonna weld solid,

05:18.235 --> 05:20.320
<i>so my best bet probably</i>

05:20.320 --> 05:21.822
<i>is to just try to untwist it</i>
<i>and square it off</i>

05:21.822 --> 05:23.281
<i>before I really</i>
<i>do anything else.</i>

05:23.281 --> 05:25.367
- Now, you did this.
- I did, yeah.

05:25.367 --> 05:27.661
- And you were saying that
when you untwist a drill bit,

05:27.661 --> 05:30.080
it doesn't twist out
into a long rectangle.

05:30.080 --> 05:32.582
- It counter-twists. It does
all sorts of weird things.

05:32.582 --> 05:34.501
If you do untwist it
an then try to square it up,

05:34.501 --> 05:37.045
you really want to be careful
not to make cold shuts.

05:37.045 --> 05:38.630
- Yeah, Alan's over here.
He's got the grinder out.

05:38.630 --> 05:40.757
He's cutting his bits in half

05:40.757 --> 05:42.676
right at the bottom
of the spiral.

05:42.676 --> 05:44.719
<i>- During the design period</i>
<i>I had a great idea</i>

05:44.719 --> 05:47.597
<i>to cut the ends off of</i>
<i>the drill bits that are round.</i>

05:47.597 --> 05:49.266
By welding those together,

05:49.266 --> 05:50.767
I will have probably
the best chance

05:50.767 --> 05:52.853
at a homogenous piece of steel.

05:52.853 --> 05:54.312
- Like you said, always a
workaround, an easy way, right?

05:54.312 --> 05:55.438
It makes it simple

05:55.438 --> 05:57.357
- I mean, it could be.

05:57.357 --> 05:58.984
The problem is you're gonna
have a lot less material.

05:58.984 --> 06:00.861
<i>- I'm taking my time,</i>

06:00.861 --> 06:02.779
<i>making sure that the steel</i>
<i>is hot enough</i>

06:02.779 --> 06:04.990
<i>but not so hot that this</i>
<i>high-carbon steel burns.</i>

06:04.990 --> 06:07.367
- Whoo, she's hot, boys.

06:07.367 --> 06:10.495
- I think Tim and Ed are going
for the same sort of technique,

06:10.495 --> 06:13.456
which is just to smash
all that steel together.

06:13.456 --> 06:15.750
<i>- With the drill bits, my plan</i>
<i>is to hammer it out,</i>

06:15.750 --> 06:18.211
get them as flat
and as straight as I can,

06:18.211 --> 06:21.798
tack-weld them, and put them
together, make them one.

06:21.798 --> 06:23.258
- Big problem with that

06:23.258 --> 06:25.343
is you're gonna
have multiple folds.

06:25.343 --> 06:27.178
- But because these drill bits
are gonna be the inner core

06:27.178 --> 06:29.347
surrounded by mild steel,
why not just flatten them out?

06:29.347 --> 06:31.975
Who cares about inclusions when
it's not really gonna be seen?

06:31.975 --> 06:33.685
- Because it's a spiral.

06:33.685 --> 06:35.312
Those cold shuts
are gonna come to the edge

06:35.312 --> 06:37.898
and come to the edge
and come to the edge.

06:37.898 --> 06:39.691
- I mean, if they
had enough heat,

06:39.691 --> 06:41.526
I wouldn't mind seeing them
brush it, flux it,

06:41.526 --> 06:43.486
and see if they can actually
weld the thing together

06:43.486 --> 06:45.113
instead of cold
shutting it together.

06:45.113 --> 06:47.991
- I've done it,
and I've been successful.

06:47.991 --> 06:49.910
I'm confident
I can pull it off.

06:49.910 --> 06:52.954
My biggest strength
as a bladesmith is my ability

06:52.954 --> 06:54.748
<i>to adapt and overcome.</i>

06:54.748 --> 06:56.750
<i>When I hurt my back,</i>

06:56.750 --> 06:58.418
<i>picked up a jackhammer</i>
<i>in the wrong position,</i>

06:58.418 --> 07:01.546
<i>and it ruptured</i>
<i>three of my discs.</i>

07:01.546 --> 07:03.590
<i>For a while</i>
<i>I was no good to anybody.</i>

07:03.590 --> 07:05.508
I couldn't hold
my infant child.

07:05.508 --> 07:08.011
I couldn't carry him.
I was broken,

07:08.011 --> 07:12.098
and then my father bought me
a little knife sharpening set.

07:12.098 --> 07:16.686
Every aspect of my life changed
once I made that first blade.

07:16.686 --> 07:18.730
<i>It gave me pride,</i>
<i>and it's something</i>

07:18.730 --> 07:20.732
that I had thought
I never would have again.

07:20.732 --> 07:24.069
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:24.069 --> 07:25.528
- So there's Tim.
This is what I like to see.

07:25.528 --> 07:27.113
He's cleaning up his steel.

07:27.113 --> 07:29.324
He's gonna get
some very clean welds.

07:29.324 --> 07:31.701
<i>- I'm cleaning it simply</i>
<i>because if you don't,</i>

07:31.701 --> 07:33.286
<i>then you run the risk</i>

07:33.286 --> 07:35.330
<i>of getting</i>
<i>some inclusions in there</i>

07:35.330 --> 07:36.956
<i>when you actually go</i>
<i>to heat it up and weld it.</i>

07:36.956 --> 07:38.416
<i>Just one little spot's</i>
<i>all it takes.</i>

07:38.416 --> 07:40.585
I just MIG welded
my first billet

07:40.585 --> 07:42.837
together out of the drill bits.
That's honestly the first time

07:42.837 --> 07:44.005
I'd ever gotten to play
with a MIG welder.

07:44.005 --> 07:45.298
Those things are pretty cool.

07:45.298 --> 07:47.592
If I can win it,
I'm buying one.

07:47.592 --> 07:50.428
<i>This forge here has so much</i>
<i>more than I have at my home.</i>

07:50.428 --> 07:53.556
I don't have a hydraulic press.
I don't have a power hammer.

07:53.556 --> 07:55.475
<i>I'm used to doing</i>
<i>everything by hand.</i>

07:55.475 --> 07:58.812
That could be my Achilles'
heel; I don't know.

07:58.812 --> 08:00.605
- Bladesmiths, you only have

08:00.605 --> 08:04.651
two hours remaining
to finish your blades!

08:04.651 --> 08:06.569
<i>- Well, I got this bit</i>
<i>where I want it now.</i>

08:06.569 --> 08:08.321
I'm just trying to decide
exactly how I'm gonna work

08:08.321 --> 08:10.907
the mild steel into it
for the construction.

08:10.907 --> 08:13.034
- There's a couple of ways
you can do the San Mai process.

08:13.034 --> 08:15.286
You can bend that mild steel
all the way around,

08:15.286 --> 08:16.788
or you can just weld two things

08:16.788 --> 08:18.331
on either side
of your high-carbon.

08:18.331 --> 08:19.791
- I've only done San Mai
a couple times.

08:19.791 --> 08:21.251
I've only used wrought
iron before,

08:21.251 --> 08:23.211
but mild is close enough,
same idea.

08:23.211 --> 08:25.046
<i>I just want to make sure</i>

08:25.046 --> 08:26.631
<i>I have enough steel</i>
<i>to get this blade done,</i>

08:26.631 --> 08:28.717
<i>so I have to</i>
<i>grind it off later.</i>

08:28.717 --> 08:30.510
That's better than trying to
figure out how to add length.

08:30.510 --> 08:32.637
- I'm a little nervous about
what Hunter's doing.

08:32.637 --> 08:35.640
It looks like he's gonna make a
passport wallet 4 inches wide.

08:35.640 --> 08:37.809
It's a lot of steel
to be working with.

08:37.809 --> 08:40.145
- I'm just gonna use that whole
piece of the mild steel, fold

08:40.145 --> 08:42.605
<i>the mild steel over</i>
<i>like a taco shell, and just</i>

08:42.605 --> 08:44.899
hook my bit in and try
to get everything welded up.

08:44.899 --> 08:46.401
- Yeah, he really could have
done that with about

08:46.401 --> 08:48.486
half that material.

08:48.486 --> 08:51.281
There's only hardenable steel
in the top inch of that,

08:51.281 --> 08:53.366
so as he drives that down,

08:53.366 --> 08:56.619
who knows where that hardened
steel's gonna wind up?

08:56.619 --> 08:58.538
- Alan's over here
folding over his steel

08:58.538 --> 09:00.957
using a similar technique.

09:00.957 --> 09:03.126
<i>- It's hard to stand out</i>
<i>when you're among smiths</i>

09:03.126 --> 09:05.420
that have much more
experience than myself,

09:05.420 --> 09:08.131
<i>but it's really going my way.</i>
<i>I can't believe it.</i>

09:08.131 --> 09:10.759
- Alan looks like he has
set himself up beautifully.

09:10.759 --> 09:13.303
That taco, he got it
in a very nice U shape,

09:13.303 --> 09:15.221
drove that hardened steel
down in the center.

09:15.221 --> 09:16.973
He's just setting
those welds up.

09:16.973 --> 09:19.434
Now, that should draw
out just beautifully.

09:19.434 --> 09:21.352
- With a ceramics background
and being able to see

09:21.352 --> 09:23.313
the color of the heat,

09:23.313 --> 09:25.273
<i>that transitions well</i>
<i>into the bladesmithing,</i>

09:25.273 --> 09:29.402
and I believe that
that'll give me an edge.

09:29.402 --> 09:31.571
- I don't know about you.

09:31.571 --> 09:33.573
Three hours seemed a whole hell
of a lot longer back home.

09:33.573 --> 09:35.325
<i>We hit that hour mark,</i>

09:35.325 --> 09:38.203
and I'm feeling like
where did I slow down?

09:38.203 --> 09:40.872
<i>My billet is thicker than</i>
<i>I thought it was gonna be,</i>

09:40.872 --> 09:43.124
and so it's just taking
its own sweet time

09:43.124 --> 09:44.834
<i>getting to that temperature</i>
<i>where I can start moving it.</i>

09:44.834 --> 09:46.878
Come on, come on,
come on, come on.

09:46.878 --> 09:48.713
<i>That clock on the wall,</i>

09:48.713 --> 09:52.008
it's like having a ton
sitting on your head.

09:52.008 --> 09:55.345
<i>I'm behind the eight ball</i>
<i>on this one.</i>

09:55.345 --> 10:00.058
- Right now the San Mai is not
cooperating with me one iota.

10:00.058 --> 10:03.353
- I think the end of
Ed's billet is opened up.

10:03.353 --> 10:05.396
- Hopefully it's just the end
of that weld.

10:05.396 --> 10:09.526
- It just doesn't want to stay.
That son of a bitch.

10:09.526 --> 10:11.111
- I'm getting a little bit
worried about Ed.

10:11.111 --> 10:13.029
- [bleep].

10:13.029 --> 10:16.032
- He looks physically
exhausted right now.

10:16.032 --> 10:18.034
- My back was all right
the first hour,

10:18.034 --> 10:20.370
and then it just went downhill.

10:20.370 --> 10:21.871
- Look at him. He's tripoding

10:21.871 --> 10:23.414
on the water barrel
in the back.

10:23.414 --> 10:28.169
- It feels much
like being burnt.

10:28.169 --> 10:30.088
<i>I'm hurting.</i>
- You doing all right?

10:30.088 --> 10:32.382
How's your back, man?
- Man, I'm on fire.

10:32.382 --> 10:34.717
My brain right now
is telling me to quit,

10:34.717 --> 10:36.845
<i>but my father, he never quit.</i>

10:36.845 --> 10:39.764
I'm not gonna let my back take
me out of here at any cost.

10:39.764 --> 10:41.766
<i>I just have to keep going.</i>

10:41.766 --> 10:43.935
- The great thing about this is
that people find a way

10:43.935 --> 10:46.271
that nothing of your own
physical limitations

10:46.271 --> 10:48.314
will stop you from
doing your passion.

10:48.314 --> 10:51.484
- But I'm still scared to
death, because I'm way behind.

10:51.484 --> 10:54.654
- Bladesmiths, two hours
has elapsed!

10:54.654 --> 10:59.367
You have just 60 minutes
remaining to finish your work!

10:59.367 --> 11:01.077
Alan's billet looks great.

11:01.077 --> 11:03.037
- It looks like one color.

11:03.037 --> 11:05.039
- The only thing that Alan has
to worry about at this point

11:05.039 --> 11:06.916
is remembering
where your hardened steel is.

11:06.916 --> 11:09.002
- While everything is going
perfectly, you know,

11:09.002 --> 11:11.296
<i>I need to be taking advantage</i>
<i>of this equipment.</i>

11:11.296 --> 11:13.214
I'm ready to attack
the power hammer.

11:13.214 --> 11:15.300
- And I hope Alan doesn't go
too narrow on that tang.

11:15.300 --> 11:16.885
- [bleep].

11:16.885 --> 11:20.388
- Oh, Big Blue
just ate his tang.

11:20.388 --> 11:22.932
- It almost got away from me.
It was kind of scary.

11:22.932 --> 11:25.602
<i>Unfortunately, the handle</i>
<i>is a little bit curved,</i>

11:25.602 --> 11:27.437
<i>and not in the direction</i>
<i>that I would like.</i>

11:27.437 --> 11:29.147
<i>I could just clip it</i>
<i>off and correct it,</i>

11:29.147 --> 11:31.149
<i>but I don't want</i>
<i>to lose a minute.</i>

11:31.149 --> 11:33.902
[bleep] damn, three hours
just isn't very long.

11:33.902 --> 11:36.154
- So you can actually see
on Hunter's piece of material

11:36.154 --> 11:38.156
how the edges are cooling
at different temperatures.

11:38.156 --> 11:40.742
- Yup.
- That indicates not welded.

11:40.742 --> 11:43.453
- Now, is that due to the
steels not sticking together,

11:43.453 --> 11:46.456
or is that just different
widths as he's forging it out?

11:46.456 --> 11:48.750
- As they're not stuck together
, the piece that peels out

11:48.750 --> 11:51.628
and is more exposed to
the air is cooling faster.

11:51.628 --> 11:53.922
- Oh, man, just can't
get it to weld right.

11:53.922 --> 11:55.840
- And it goes back to
preparation again.

11:55.840 --> 11:57.300
Did he clean the metal?

11:57.300 --> 11:59.052
- Well, we see it
again and again.

11:59.052 --> 12:01.179
The cleaner you can
make that material,

12:01.179 --> 12:03.765
the better those welds
are gonna be on the first try.

12:03.765 --> 12:07.310
The best steel we've seen
is always off the clean stuff.

12:07.310 --> 12:09.896
- Is it not sticking?
- Not in a couple spots.

12:09.896 --> 12:12.190
- You get another fire brick
to close up the other end?

12:12.190 --> 12:13.316
- Hopefully I can get it to go.

12:13.316 --> 12:15.109
- Well, don't give up, man.

12:15.109 --> 12:16.527
<i>- I'm really running</i>
<i>out of time,</i>

12:16.527 --> 12:18.154
but there's no point
going forward

12:18.154 --> 12:21.532
if I don't have
those welds closed up.

12:21.532 --> 12:24.535
- Tim's working that seax tip
into his blade now.

12:24.535 --> 12:25.995
<i>- I got the bevels</i>
<i>rough forged,</i>

12:25.995 --> 12:27.789
and the handle's in there.

12:27.789 --> 12:29.666
I wish it was a little
bit wider on the tip.

12:29.666 --> 12:31.334
<i>Thought I was gonna have</i>
<i>at least a half hour</i>

12:31.334 --> 12:32.627
<i>to address anything</i>
<i>that I wanted to.</i>

12:32.627 --> 12:34.545
I don't have that time anymore.

12:34.545 --> 12:36.589
- Ten minutes, bladesmiths!

12:36.589 --> 12:39.592
<i>- I've got to get this blade</i>
<i>heated up and quenched.</i>

12:39.592 --> 12:43.096
- Oh, look, Tim is in the oil.

12:43.096 --> 12:45.431
- Tim is our first smith
to quench.

12:45.431 --> 12:47.267
I'm really surprised by that.

12:47.267 --> 12:50.270
- So far, so good.
- Hunter's in the quench.

12:50.270 --> 12:51.437
Alan quenched just now.

12:51.437 --> 12:53.022
- All right, there we go.

12:53.022 --> 12:54.857
- Ed's gonna go
for one more heat,

12:54.857 --> 12:57.694
doesn't leave him any time
to correct warps

12:57.694 --> 13:00.280
if they develop in the quench.

13:00.280 --> 13:02.532
<i>- Right now I'm behind</i>
<i>everyone else.</i>

13:02.532 --> 13:04.534
I have to get this blade
in the quench.

13:04.534 --> 13:06.452
I'm running out of time,
and if I don't,

13:06.452 --> 13:09.038
<i>I go home without</i>
<i>even looking at my stuff.</i>

13:09.038 --> 13:13.835
- Two minutes!
- Okay, here we go.

13:13.835 --> 13:15.670
<i>I pull the blade up</i>
<i>out of the oil,</i>

13:15.670 --> 13:18.673
and there's a slight warp
near the end.

13:18.673 --> 13:20.091
Mother of [bleep] pearl.

13:20.091 --> 13:23.386
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:23.386 --> 13:27.140
- Ten, nine, eight, seven,

13:27.140 --> 13:29.976
six, five, four,

13:29.976 --> 13:33.521
three, two, one.

13:33.521 --> 13:35.732
Bladesmiths, drop your tools!

13:35.732 --> 13:37.650
This forging round is over!

13:37.650 --> 13:39.319
[laughter and applause]

13:39.319 --> 13:41.988
- [bleep] damn we worked hard.
- Damn.

13:41.988 --> 13:44.907
<i>- I feel proud that I made</i>
<i>a piece of San Mai steel</i>

13:44.907 --> 13:46.868
<i>that I think is solid.</i>

13:46.868 --> 13:48.786
May not have done it well,
but well, I've done it.

13:48.786 --> 13:51.039
- That's an ugly son
of a bitch.

13:51.039 --> 13:53.791
So I'm just really hoping
that I got the good steel

13:53.791 --> 13:55.668
<i>where I needed</i>
<i>it along the edge.</i>

13:55.668 --> 13:57.712
I feel like if I got too many
cracks along those edge,

13:57.712 --> 14:00.923
I'm definitely not gonna be
making it to the second round.

14:00.923 --> 14:02.633
- Bladesmiths, it's time
for the judges

14:02.633 --> 14:04.677
to take a closer
look at your work.

14:04.677 --> 14:06.262
Alan, you're up first.

14:06.262 --> 14:08.931
Please present your work
to the judges.

14:08.931 --> 14:11.768
<i>- I really enjoyed watching you</i>
<i>do your forge welds.</i>

14:11.768 --> 14:13.269
Everything seemed
to be going well,

14:13.269 --> 14:14.479
and then something
must have happened

14:14.479 --> 14:16.064
'cause this is really thin.

14:16.064 --> 14:17.690
For a coconut chop
I might have wanted

14:17.690 --> 14:19.609
it just a little bit
thicker than that.

14:19.609 --> 14:22.862
- I'm just gonna ask the
question. Was that intentional?

14:22.862 --> 14:25.364
- I intended for
the handle to go down.

14:25.364 --> 14:28.659
I lost track of which edge
the San Mai was folded in.

14:28.659 --> 14:30.620
- Got you, okay.

14:30.620 --> 14:32.830
<i>You might really want</i>
<i>to address that handle.</i>

14:32.830 --> 14:35.958
Right now
it's just very awkward.

14:35.958 --> 14:39.212
- Hunter, please present
your blade to the judges.

14:39.212 --> 14:42.381
<i>- Well, Hunter, watching you</i>
<i>do the San Mai welds,</i>

14:42.381 --> 14:44.717
the surfaces weren't very
clean, so that's why

14:44.717 --> 14:47.136
I think you were fighting
this weld for so long.

14:47.136 --> 14:49.639
<i>There is still some problems</i>
<i>up here at the tip</i>

14:49.639 --> 14:51.766
that if you go forward

14:51.766 --> 14:53.810
would need to be ground out
and just see where you are.

14:53.810 --> 14:57.313
- All right, Ed, please present
your work to the judges.

14:57.313 --> 14:59.232
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:59.232 --> 15:00.983
<i>- Well, Ed,</i>
<i>watching you work out there,</i>

15:00.983 --> 15:02.360
<i>I can see how much pain</i>
<i>you were in.</i>

15:02.360 --> 15:04.612
I know you have a bad back,

15:04.612 --> 15:06.864
but what I even saw better was
the mettle that's inside you.

15:06.864 --> 15:10.368
You don't let anything stop you
from doing what you love,

15:10.368 --> 15:12.620
and I commend that.

15:12.620 --> 15:15.414
- Well, Ed, I like where
you're heading with this knife.

15:15.414 --> 15:18.251
I like the shape, but I mean,

15:18.251 --> 15:20.670
there's deep fissures
on the top here,

15:20.670 --> 15:23.506
<i>and I'm not 100%</i>
<i>sure that it's welded.</i>

15:23.506 --> 15:25.341
There's almost rattling in
there.

15:25.341 --> 15:29.345
- Yeah, well.
- All right, Tim, you're up.

15:29.345 --> 15:31.430
<i>- I liked where you were</i>
<i>going with this,</i>

15:31.430 --> 15:34.267
but I would have loved to have
seen that peak being up here,

15:34.267 --> 15:36.269
you know,
another 3/4 of an inch

15:36.269 --> 15:38.521
to really give it
that brokeback seax look.

15:38.521 --> 15:42.275
If you move forward,
try not to lose too much mass.

15:42.275 --> 15:44.402
- One thing I'm not a huge fan
of is this handle.

15:44.402 --> 15:46.779
It's a little small
for my hand.

15:46.779 --> 15:48.197
Be interesting to see
if there's anything

15:48.197 --> 15:50.116
that can be done there,

15:50.116 --> 15:54.328
but all in all
it's a solidly welded piece.

15:54.328 --> 15:56.497
Well done.

15:56.497 --> 15:57.957
- All right, bladesmiths, the
judges have a final decision

15:57.957 --> 15:59.458
to make about
which of you moves on

15:59.458 --> 16:01.002
to our next round
of competition.

16:01.002 --> 16:02.128
While they do that,
I'm gonna have you

16:02.128 --> 16:03.629
leave your blades on this table

16:03.629 --> 16:05.089
and step off the Forge floor.

16:05.089 --> 16:08.509
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:08.509 --> 16:11.429
<i>[tense music]</i>

16:11.429 --> 16:17.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:17.643 --> 16:20.354
- Okay, judges, our bladesmiths
have turned in their weapons.

16:20.354 --> 16:22.023
Now it's time
to get into the details.

16:22.023 --> 16:24.066
Only three of them
can move forward,

16:24.066 --> 16:27.195
so is there a blade here that
is definitely moving forward?

16:27.195 --> 16:28.821
- Yeah.
- Ben.

16:28.821 --> 16:30.323
- Tim did a good
job with his forge welds.

16:30.323 --> 16:34.035
He cleaned everything up
really nicely.

16:34.035 --> 16:36.287
In all, it's a solid piece.

16:36.287 --> 16:38.664
- All right, let's move on to
Alan's blade here on the end.

16:38.664 --> 16:41.083
- That's your baby.
- That is.

16:41.083 --> 16:43.711
<i>- Alan started with</i>
<i>a really good forge weld.</i>

16:43.711 --> 16:45.338
In all, it's a solid piece.

16:45.338 --> 16:47.381
- He did say that he lost
track of the edge.

16:47.381 --> 16:49.133
Does he actually know

16:49.133 --> 16:50.927
where the hardenable steel
is on this edge?

16:50.927 --> 16:53.429
- There's one way to find out.

16:55.056 --> 16:56.474
Yup, it's hard all the way up.

16:56.474 --> 16:58.809
- All right, cool.

16:58.809 --> 17:01.145
- The big issue is that handle.
Obviously he has it reversed.

17:01.145 --> 17:03.314
If he moves forward,
he needs to bring it down

17:03.314 --> 17:05.274
to where it feels
like a chop.

17:05.274 --> 17:09.070
Right now it's not in line
with my fist right there.

17:09.070 --> 17:10.863
- All right, let's move on
to our next bladesmith,

17:10.863 --> 17:14.909
and that is Hunter.

17:14.909 --> 17:16.911
<i>- My big problem was all</i>
<i>of the trouble</i>

17:16.911 --> 17:18.162
<i>he was having</i>
<i>with the forge weld.</i>

17:18.162 --> 17:20.248
<i>It's just not as solid and hard</i>

17:20.248 --> 17:22.166
as you could get
if you had clean surfaces.

17:22.166 --> 17:23.918
- Okay.
- My one worry is that

17:23.918 --> 17:26.003
I don't know

17:26.003 --> 17:27.129
that the hardened edge
is in the middle all the time,

17:27.129 --> 17:28.756
so there are sections back here

17:28.756 --> 17:31.050
that don't have hardened
steel at the edge.

17:31.050 --> 17:32.802
- When he was welding that,

17:32.802 --> 17:35.513
we actually saw that
his two pieces of mild steel,

17:35.513 --> 17:36.806
they were kind of offset,

17:36.806 --> 17:38.474
so it could have easily

17:38.474 --> 17:40.434
have lipped over the top
of the hardened steel.

17:40.434 --> 17:42.270
- Yeah.
- If he grinds that all away,

17:42.270 --> 17:44.438
it could just be
a steel core underneath.

17:44.438 --> 17:46.691
- It needs a lot of work
to get back to the steel.

17:46.691 --> 17:48.401
- Okay. Let's move on
to our next bladesmith.

17:48.401 --> 17:52.071
That's Ed.

17:52.071 --> 17:54.574
- There's so little grinding
and refining on this.

17:54.574 --> 17:56.492
I look at these,

17:56.492 --> 17:58.452
and it's like I can get
a fingernail in there.

17:58.452 --> 18:00.246
It's almost like
if you put a chisel on it

18:00.246 --> 18:03.332
<i>and hit it right there,</i>
<i>you'd pull a section up.</i>

18:03.332 --> 18:04.834
That's what I'm worried
about, though,

18:04.834 --> 18:07.753
that there's
a giant pocket there.

18:07.753 --> 18:09.297
- All right, judges,
I need to know.

18:09.297 --> 18:10.798
Have you made
your final decision?

18:10.798 --> 18:14.176
- Yes.
- Let's go tell our smiths.

18:14.176 --> 18:16.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:16.137 --> 18:18.639
Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete,

18:18.639 --> 18:24.353
and they have made
their final decision.

18:24.353 --> 18:26.188
cision.

18:26.188 --> 18:27.523
It's time for one of you
to leave the Forge.

18:27.523 --> 18:31.736
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:31.736 --> 18:35.072
The bladesmith leaving
the Forge is Ed.

18:35.072 --> 18:36.866
Your blade did not
make the cut.

18:36.866 --> 18:38.951
David Baker's gonna
tell you why.

18:38.951 --> 18:41.078
- Ed, I really appreciate
all the work you did to set up

18:41.078 --> 18:42.955
for that weld,

18:42.955 --> 18:44.915
<i>but with that material</i>
<i>being so thin,</i>

18:44.915 --> 18:46.959
<i>some of those welds</i>
<i>are questionable,</i>

18:46.959 --> 18:50.004
<i>and of all four of our blades,</i>
<i>yours is least finished,</i>

18:50.004 --> 18:52.882
and that's why
we're letting you go.

18:52.882 --> 18:56.052
- Ed, please
surrender your blade.

18:56.052 --> 18:58.054
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:58.054 --> 19:00.890
- This experience was the heat
in my life

19:00.890 --> 19:03.100
<i>I needed to forge myself</i>
<i>into a better person</i>

19:03.100 --> 19:04.894
<i>and a better knife maker.</i>

19:04.894 --> 19:07.938
It saved my life.
I'll never stop making knives.

19:07.938 --> 19:11.692
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:11.692 --> 19:13.611
- All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

19:13.611 --> 19:16.113
You've made it to the second
round of this competition.

19:16.113 --> 19:18.491
All you have to do now
is take those tempered blades

19:18.491 --> 19:20.326
and turn them into
fully functional weapons

19:20.326 --> 19:22.328
by attaching handles to them

19:22.328 --> 19:23.788
using the range of material
provided in our pantry,

19:23.788 --> 19:26.165
and since your blades
are San Mai,

19:26.165 --> 19:27.541
which means that they have
two different types

19:27.541 --> 19:28.918
of steels in them,

19:28.918 --> 19:30.670
we're also requiring
that you use

19:30.670 --> 19:33.589
at least two different types
of handle material

19:33.589 --> 19:36.842
in your handle's design
and construction.

19:36.842 --> 19:38.636
You will have three hours
in this round.

19:38.636 --> 19:40.763
Now, you can use some of
that time to address flaws

19:40.763 --> 19:42.598
and issues that were
identified in your blades

19:42.598 --> 19:43.974
because your weapons
will be tested

19:43.974 --> 19:45.267
for strength and durability

19:45.267 --> 19:47.144
in a coconut chop

19:47.144 --> 19:51.232
and for edge retention
in a ratchet strap slice.

19:51.232 --> 19:54.110
When the time runs out and
your blades have been tested,

19:54.110 --> 19:55.528
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

19:55.528 --> 19:57.071
and leave the Forge.

19:57.071 --> 19:59.865
Good luck.
Your time starts now.

19:59.865 --> 20:03.285
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:03.285 --> 20:06.330
- The biggest critique that
I took at the end of round one

20:06.330 --> 20:09.208
was that the handle
went the wrong direction.

20:09.208 --> 20:11.043
- Let's start with Alan
over here.

20:11.043 --> 20:13.421
It looks like he's gonna use
the acetylene torch

20:13.421 --> 20:15.923
to heat up his tang.

20:15.923 --> 20:18.634
<i>- I wrap the blade</i>
<i>in a paper towel</i>

20:18.634 --> 20:20.469
<i>and submerse it in water</i>

