- [laughs]

22:02.196 --> 22:04.532
<i>- I chose one acrylic scale</i>
<i>and one wood scale</i>

22:04.532 --> 22:08.160
to make sure that I had time
to do a simple handle.

22:08.160 --> 22:09.995
- How's she coming, man?
- Coming along.

22:09.995 --> 22:11.872
- Looking pretty?
- I got the epoxy set,

22:11.872 --> 22:13.666
so hope I didn't miss anything
before I got there.

22:13.666 --> 22:15.501
- Ooh, damn, man,
you're flying.

22:15.501 --> 22:18.546
- The bladesmiths in this
competition have really

22:18.546 --> 22:19.713
become a brotherhood.

22:19.713 --> 22:21.131
Gorgeous, dude.

22:21.131 --> 22:23.133
- Thanks, man.

22:23.133 --> 22:24.260
- We've all banded together.
We've shared ideas.

22:24.260 --> 22:26.053
We've shared information.

22:26.053 --> 22:27.763
I think it goes well
beyond the competition.

22:27.763 --> 22:30.641
<i>This is just a passion</i>
<i>for what we do.</i>

22:30.641 --> 22:32.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:32.643 --> 22:33.811
<i>- I find this pretty</i>
<i>cool-looking acrylics,</i>

22:33.811 --> 22:36.105
<i>black and green.</i>

22:36.105 --> 22:37.439
<i>It's got a neat-looking pattern</i>
<i>to it, and I have some wood</i>

22:37.439 --> 22:38.649
that'll make simple scales
to go

22:38.649 --> 22:40.734
on the bottom of the blade.

22:40.734 --> 22:42.695
<i>Altogether I'm using</i>
<i>four pins for this handle.</i>

22:42.695 --> 22:43.904
I'm making sure
everything's lined up,

22:43.904 --> 22:45.656
and the best way to do that

22:45.656 --> 22:47.783
and know for sure the hole's
in the right spot

22:47.783 --> 22:49.493
is to drill through the other
holes it's gonna meet up with.

22:49.493 --> 22:52.913
- I'm not sure what he's doing.
- Oh, here we go.

22:52.913 --> 22:54.915
- Whoa.
- Helicopter, oh

22:54.915 --> 22:56.750
- Whoa, whoa.

22:56.750 --> 22:58.127
- That didn't work like
I thought it would.

22:58.127 --> 23:00.254
- So that is a strange
technique.

23:00.254 --> 23:02.923
- I don't think that Hunter's
gonna have very even holes.

23:02.923 --> 23:05.509
- These new scales, they're not
quite the look I really wanted,

23:05.509 --> 23:08.095
but honestly, the looks
are secondary to anything else.

23:08.095 --> 23:11.181
They'll just have to do.
It doesn't have to be pretty.

23:11.181 --> 23:12.933
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:12.933 --> 23:14.184
- Looks like Tim
didn't get the memo

23:14.184 --> 23:15.436
that we have clamps for that.

23:15.436 --> 23:18.105
[laughter]

23:18.105 --> 23:19.899
<i>- I grabbed a horn</i>
<i>because I like the pattern,</i>

23:19.899 --> 23:21.859
<i>and the wood,</i>

23:21.859 --> 23:23.736
I've worked with this
kind of wood before,

23:23.736 --> 23:27.698
and I know that it'll
actually take a finish.

23:27.698 --> 23:29.658
- That water buffalo horn
is real nice.

23:29.658 --> 23:31.660
If he polishes that up,
it'll look slick.

23:31.660 --> 23:32.995
- Yeah.

23:32.995 --> 23:34.872
- Pretty bomb-proof stuff too.

23:34.872 --> 23:36.373
I've used it for full-size
handles on swords,

23:36.373 --> 23:40.044
and it's almost
impossible to break.

23:40.044 --> 23:43.380
- I'm very happy with the look
and the feel of the handle.

23:43.380 --> 23:44.882
- There you go.
He's slacking on the back side.

23:44.882 --> 23:46.926
He's turned it sideways,

23:46.926 --> 23:48.302
and he's slacking on what would
have been the bottom.

23:48.302 --> 23:49.929
- I'm not on top--I'm not
on the top.

23:49.929 --> 23:51.597
- Hey, it's not a bad idea.
- Yeah.

23:51.597 --> 23:52.932
<i>- I used the slack belt</i>
<i>on the bottom</i>

23:52.932 --> 23:55.726
<i>to clean up parts of the blade</i>

23:55.726 --> 23:58.145
without removing
too much material.

23:58.145 --> 24:02.524
I feel that that will put
the best edge on my blade.

24:02.524 --> 24:04.068
- So that noise we're hearing

24:04.068 --> 24:07.112
is him testing
his edge geometry.

24:07.112 --> 24:08.280
- With gusto!

24:08.280 --> 24:09.865
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:09.865 --> 24:11.408
<i>- I want to make sure</i>

24:11.408 --> 24:13.077
I have this edge
geometry set up properly

24:13.077 --> 24:14.954
to actually handle
the challenge,

24:14.954 --> 24:16.789
<i>so while I'm grinding</i>
<i>the edge onto the blade,</i>

24:16.789 --> 24:20.542
I'm going until I actually
get an apex to that edge

24:20.542 --> 24:22.461
<i>to where it actually</i>
<i>catches, like,</i>

24:22.461 --> 24:25.047
on the thumbnails; it's sharp
enough to actually dig in.

24:25.047 --> 24:26.757
- You know, Hunter's
got a large convex

24:26.757 --> 24:28.509
grind on that blade,

24:28.509 --> 24:30.678
and it should hold up
pretty well to coconuts.

24:30.678 --> 24:34.431
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:34.431 --> 24:39.269
Ten, nine, eight, seven, six,

24:39.269 --> 24:41.313
five, four,

24:41.313 --> 24:44.608
three, two, one.

24:44.608 --> 24:47.069
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines.

24:47.069 --> 24:49.530
Get ready for
the weapons tests.

24:49.530 --> 24:52.199
- I made a blade that I feel
is definitely ugly.

24:52.199 --> 24:53.617
It's definitely not
the prettiest thing

24:53.617 --> 24:55.828
I've ever forged, but it's big.

24:55.828 --> 24:59.164
It's strong, and I think
it'll handle these challenges.

24:59.164 --> 25:00.874
- Bladesmiths, this is
the strength test,

25:00.874 --> 25:02.626
the coconut chop.

25:02.626 --> 25:04.586
To test the strength
and durability of your edges,

25:04.586 --> 25:06.005
I'm gonna be taking your blades

25:06.005 --> 25:07.798
and chopping into
these coconuts.

25:07.798 --> 25:09.341
Remember, this test
is all about

25:09.341 --> 25:10.926
what the coconuts do
to your blades

25:10.926 --> 25:13.721
and not what your knives
do to the coconuts.

25:13.721 --> 25:15.514
Alan, you're up. You ready?

25:15.514 --> 25:17.057
- Absolutely. Let's do it.

25:17.057 --> 25:18.892
<i>It puts a lot of pressure on me</i>

25:18.892 --> 25:21.645
<i>having a coconut chop</i>
<i>as the challenge.</i>

25:21.645 --> 25:24.982
<i>The Coconut Empire Forge</i>
<i>was meant to chop coconuts.</i>

25:24.982 --> 25:28.152
<i>We're gonna make it happen.</i>

25:28.152 --> 25:34.283
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:34.283 --> 25:35.743
- Damn.
- Whew.

25:35.743 --> 25:38.162
- Damn.
- Yes.

25:38.162 --> 25:40.372
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:40.372 --> 25:42.708
- Well, Alan, the handle
is really narrow,

25:42.708 --> 25:45.169
but I could--I could hold
onto it really well,

25:45.169 --> 25:48.964
but you put a really fine
edge on this blade,

25:48.964 --> 25:51.091
and it picked up a roll here

25:51.091 --> 25:53.469
<i>and another small one</i>
<i>right next to it.</i>

25:53.469 --> 25:57.097
In all, there's no chipping,
and it held up. Well done.

25:57.097 --> 25:58.682
- Thank you.
- Hunter, you're up next.

25:58.682 --> 26:00.267
You ready?
- Oh, yeah.

26:00.267 --> 26:02.352
<i>I know I got this one.</i>

26:02.352 --> 26:04.146
<i>This blade's so heavy,</i>
<i>whether it's sharp or not,</i>

26:04.146 --> 26:06.023
<i>it's going through,</i>
<i>but I just got to hope</i>

26:06.023 --> 26:07.649
<i>I maintained</i>
<i>that hard steel on the edge</i>

26:07.649 --> 26:08.567
<i>and that nothing bad happens.</i>

26:08.567 --> 26:15.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:19.036 --> 26:21.455
Yeah.
- Sweet.

26:21.455 --> 26:23.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:23.457 --> 26:25.959
- Well, Hunter, first off,
your edge held up really well.

26:25.959 --> 26:28.712
It's not super-duper sharp.

26:28.712 --> 26:30.589
I feel pretty safe
running my fingers across here

26:30.589 --> 26:32.716
without getting cut,

26:32.716 --> 26:35.302
but it held up really well.
Tim, you're up next. You ready?

26:35.302 --> 26:36.929
- Oh, yeah.
- All right.

26:36.929 --> 26:39.640
- More than.
<i>I am dying up here.</i>

26:39.640 --> 26:41.642
<i>I just want to see</i>
<i>that knife come down.</i>

26:41.642 --> 26:43.352
<i>I want to see coconuts</i>
<i>shredded.</i>

26:43.352 --> 26:50.317
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:55.823 --> 26:57.908
- As long as the edge
held up, you're good.

26:57.908 --> 27:01.745
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:01.745 --> 27:04.915
- Well, Tim, your edge
held up beautifully,

27:04.915 --> 27:07.376
but for a chopper, this handle,
it's kind of round,

27:07.376 --> 27:10.462
and on the second coconut it
just turned in my hand

27:10.462 --> 27:11.380
and glanced off.

27:11.380 --> 27:15.175
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:15.175 --> 27:16.593
But other than that, well done.

27:16.593 --> 27:18.095
- Thank you.

27:18.095 --> 27:19.555
- Next up is
the sharpness test,

27:19.555 --> 27:20.597
and for that
I give you to Doug.

27:20.597 --> 27:22.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:22.641 --> 27:26.770
- Bladesmiths, this is
the ratchet strap slash.

27:26.770 --> 27:29.189
Now, a sharp weapon
should cut cleanly through.

27:29.189 --> 27:31.358
Unlike the coconut test,

27:31.358 --> 27:34.987
this is all about what your
blade does to these straps.

27:34.987 --> 27:36.363
Alan, you're up first.
You ready?

27:36.363 --> 27:38.365
- Yes, sir.

27:38.365 --> 27:40.576
With the damage that I incurred
on the coconut chop,

27:40.576 --> 27:42.578
I'm a little concerned about

27:42.578 --> 27:43.620
<i>how it's gonna go through</i>
<i>the ratchet straps.</i>

27:43.620 --> 27:50.627
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:52.004 --> 27:53.797
- All right, Alan, let's talk
about your blade here.

27:53.797 --> 27:55.549
It still is sharp,

27:55.549 --> 27:58.760
but your edge took damage
on the strength test,

27:58.760 --> 28:00.929
and when I'm slashing
through these ratchet straps,

28:00.929 --> 28:03.849
you can tell because
some areas of this,

28:03.849 --> 28:05.434
it tore through it.

28:05.434 --> 28:09.521
Overall,
though, your weapon will cut.

28:09.521 --> 28:10.689
- Thank you.
- Hunter, you're up next.

28:10.689 --> 28:12.065
You ready?

28:12.065 --> 28:13.984
- I guess.
- Let's do this.

28:13.984 --> 28:15.652
<i>- The blade's not as sharp</i>
<i>as I'd like it.</i>

28:15.652 --> 28:18.238
All I can think is when
they go into that strap,

28:18.238 --> 28:20.574
<i>I'm afraid it's gonna</i>
<i>just bounce off.</i>

28:20.574 --> 28:26.872
<i>If it won't even cut a strap,</i>
<i>there's no way I'm moving on.</i>

28:26.872 --> 28:29.958
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:29.958 --> 28:32.544
Yes!

28:32.544 --> 28:34.713
- All right Hunter, let's talk
about your blade here.

28:34.713 --> 28:38.717
When you slice through it,
you can see that it tore

28:38.717 --> 28:42.220
some parts of this
particular strap right here,

28:42.220 --> 28:45.140
but the weight of this cuts and
pushes through all the weight.

28:45.140 --> 28:46.767
It will cut.

28:46.767 --> 28:48.143
- Thank you.
- Tim, you're up next.

28:48.143 --> 28:49.436
You ready?

28:49.436 --> 28:51.647
- As I'm ever gonna be.

28:51.647 --> 28:53.482
I'm worried about
my handle indexing

28:53.482 --> 28:56.735
because if it rolls,
it's gonna glance off.

28:56.735 --> 28:58.070
I'm done.

28:58.070 --> 29:02.950
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:02.950 --> 29:05.661
- Nice, dude.
- I can breathe again.

29:05.661 --> 29:07.454
- All right, Tim, let's talk
about your blade here.

29:07.454 --> 29:09.498
First up, your handle,

29:09.498 --> 29:11.541
it's on the smaller,
narrow side, but you know what?

29:11.541 --> 29:13.919
It's comfortable
when I grabbed onto it.

29:13.919 --> 29:15.921
Your edge, it's razor sharp.

29:15.921 --> 29:20.258
It pretty much cut all the way
through, and it will cut.

29:20.258 --> 29:22.427
- Thank God.
- Good job.

29:22.427 --> 29:24.346
- This looks pretty neck
and neck.

29:24.346 --> 29:26.598
It's all down to the judges,
I think, on this one.

29:26.598 --> 29:29.518
<i>I feel like we all have a one</i>
<i>in three chance of going home.</i>

29:29.518 --> 29:31.186
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:31.186 --> 29:32.896
- All right, bladesmiths,

29:32.896 --> 29:34.898
the judges have made
their final decision.

29:34.898 --> 29:36.858
The bladesmith leaving
the Forge is...

29:36.858 --> 29:41.279
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:41.279 --> 29:43.198
Alan.

29:43.198 --> 29:45.200
Your blade did not
make the cut.

29:45.200 --> 29:46.994
Ben's gonna tell you why.

29:46.994 --> 29:50.372
- Alan, I loved watching you
set up for your San Mai,

29:50.372 --> 29:52.290
<i>but during the strength test</i>

29:52.290 --> 29:53.959
<i>your blade took some</i>
<i>pretty serious damage,</i>

29:53.959 --> 29:55.335
and that caused it
to underperform

29:55.335 --> 29:57.587
in the sharpness test as well,

29:57.587 --> 30:00.173
and it's for those reasons we
are gonna have to let you go.

30:00.173 --> 30:03.176
- Alan, please
surrender your blade.

30:03.176 --> 30:05.220
<i>- I agree with the judges'</i>
<i>decision.</i>

30:05.220 --> 30:08.932
My blade incurred just too much
damage striking those coconuts.

30:08.932 --> 30:11.018
<i>This competition has</i>
<i>definitely stoked the fire</i>

30:11.018 --> 30:12.728
<i>of my bladesmithing passion,</i>

30:12.728 --> 30:15.022
and I will continue
to develop skills.

30:15.022 --> 30:18.316
<i>The Coconut Empire has only</i>
<i>lost the battle, not the war.</i>

30:18.316 --> 30:21.611
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:21.611 --> 30:23.989
- Hunter, Tim, congratulations.
You guys have made it

30:23.989 --> 30:25.907
to the final round
of this competition,

30:25.907 --> 30:28.076
which means that you're both
one step closer to the title

30:28.076 --> 30:29.661
of "Forged in Fire" champion

30:29.661 --> 30:32.497
and that check for $10,000.

30:32.497 --> 30:35.083
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

30:35.083 --> 30:37.419
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

30:37.419 --> 30:39.546
That weapon is...

30:39.546 --> 30:41.339
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:41.339 --> 30:42.799
The kelewang.

30:42.799 --> 30:44.676
- [exhales]

30:44.676 --> 30:46.803
- All right.

30:46.803 --> 30:48.805
<i>- One of Malaysia's deadliest</i>
<i>traditional weapons,</i>

30:48.805 --> 30:50.640
<i>the kelewang is</i>
<i>a single-edged sword</i>

30:50.640 --> 30:53.643
<i>used in tribal warfare</i>
<i>in the 18th century.</i>

30:53.643 --> 30:56.438
<i>This light short sword with its</i>
<i>curved belly and clipped tip</i>

30:56.438 --> 30:59.858
<i>was a brutal slasher</i>
<i>and stabber.</i>

30:59.858 --> 31:02.110
<i>During its brief</i>
<i>rule of Malaysia,</i>

31:02.110 --> 31:04.279
<i>the Dutch colonial government</i>
<i>deemed the sword so lethal,</i>

31:04.279 --> 31:06.615
<i>they banned it from use before</i>
<i>developing their own version</i>

31:06.615 --> 31:08.784
<i>to quell uprisings.</i>

31:08.784 --> 31:11.078
<i>With ornate features like</i>
<i>an elaborately carved hilt</i>

31:11.078 --> 31:12.871
<i>or an intricate hook</i>
<i>on the spine,</i>

31:12.871 --> 31:14.873
<i>the kelewang became</i>
<i>an elegant accessory</i>

31:14.873 --> 31:17.125
<i>worn at formal events.</i>

31:17.125 --> 31:19.461
<i>Today its Dutch counterpart</i>
<i>is still worn in ceremonies</i>

31:19.461 --> 31:21.755
<i>by the Royal Netherlands Army.</i>

31:21.755 --> 31:24.424
It must be an effective
working version of that weapon.

31:24.424 --> 31:27.636
However, there must be
a decorative loop

31:27.636 --> 31:29.304
in the spine of the blade,

31:29.304 --> 31:32.474
and your handle must be
at least 12 inches long.

31:32.474 --> 31:34.101
Bladesmiths, you will have
five days at your home

31:34.101 --> 31:36.061
forges to complete
this project.

31:36.061 --> 31:38.188
At the end of five days
you will return and present

31:38.188 --> 31:40.190
your kelewangs to our judges,

31:40.190 --> 31:42.109
and only after they've
tested them thoroughly

31:42.109 --> 31:44.694
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

31:44.694 --> 31:47.030
and hand you that
check for 10 grand.

31:47.030 --> 31:49.407
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

31:49.407 --> 31:54.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:54.496 --> 31:56.373
<i>- Just made it back</i>
<i>to the home forge.</i>

31:56.373 --> 31:58.959
<i>I'm making</i>
<i>an Indonesian kelewang.</i>

31:58.959 --> 32:00.919
<i>I want this thing to be, like,</i>

32:00.919 --> 32:04.464
amazing just to look at
and then cut a pig in half.

32:04.464 --> 32:06.550
<i>Since round one was San Mai,</i>

32:06.550 --> 32:09.094
<i>what I'm gonna try to do</i>
<i>is do a Go Mai construction.</i>

32:09.094 --> 32:10.971
<i>Go Mai is like San Mai,</i>

32:10.971 --> 32:12.514
<i>but instead of three layers,</i>
<i>it's five.</i>

32:12.514 --> 32:15.308
It should look amazing
once it's etched.

32:15.308 --> 32:17.561
<i>Tim's really good</i>
<i>at what he does.</i>

32:17.561 --> 32:19.729
<i>I'm thinking that his blade</i>
<i>is gonna perform very well.</i>

32:19.729 --> 32:21.857
<i>I think mine will too.</i>

32:21.857 --> 32:23.650
That's every bit of 15 pounds,
and it ain't falling,

32:23.650 --> 32:25.527
so I'll take it.

32:25.527 --> 32:27.195
<i>If they both pass</i>
<i>all the challenges,</i>

32:27.195 --> 32:29.114
<i>having this Go Mai construction</i>

32:29.114 --> 32:31.032
<i>is gonna give me</i>
<i>the edge and let me win.</i>

32:31.032 --> 32:33.368
Okay.

32:33.368 --> 32:35.287
Definitely not
the easiest thing

32:35.287 --> 32:37.747
I could have chose to do,

32:37.747 --> 32:39.875
but I think I can pull it off.

32:39.875 --> 32:43.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:43.670 --> 32:46.298
<i>- Being back in the home forge,</i>
<i>it's a totally different game.</i>

32:46.298 --> 32:48.175
<i>I don't have a power hammer.</i>

32:48.175 --> 32:49.676
I don't have a hydraulic press.

32:49.676 --> 32:51.386
<i>Everything I've got in my shop</i>

32:51.386 --> 32:52.470
<i>you can pick up</i>
<i>at a hardware store.</i>

32:52.470 --> 32:54.055
I just picked up a Hay Budden,

32:54.055 --> 32:56.057
got a really smoking
deal on this one.

32:56.057 --> 32:57.893
<i>The challenge</i>
<i>that we got handed,</i>

32:57.893 --> 33:00.729
it didn't make any sense
when I was looking at it.

33:00.729 --> 33:02.314
<i>It's got to have a curve.</i>

33:02.314 --> 33:05.233
<i>It's got to have</i>
<i>a fricking hook.</i>

33:05.233 --> 33:08.195
<i>The biggest challenge is just</i>
<i>gonna be putting that hook.</i>

33:09.696 --> 33:12.741
<i>I'm gonna try and get</i>
<i>two blades forged out.</i>

33:12.741 --> 33:14.868
<i>I want to make sure that</i>
<i>if something does happen,</i>

33:14.868 --> 33:16.912
<i>I've got a backup.</i>

33:16.912 --> 33:19.873
I don't want to walk into this
on day three and snap,

33:19.873 --> 33:21.750
there goes a blade.

33:21.750 --> 33:23.168
Now I've got to start
all over from nothing.

33:23.168 --> 33:25.754
<i>I want to win it.</i>

33:25.754 --> 33:27.672
<i>- Yesterday I managed</i>
<i>to get this big,</i>

33:27.672 --> 33:30.300
<i>ugly billet drawn</i>
<i>out to the length I need.</i>

33:30.300 --> 33:33.220
Today I need to get this thing
into its final shape.

33:33.220 --> 33:35.430
<i>This hook on the back,</i>

33:35.430 --> 33:37.349
<i>it's just gonna be a little bit</i>
<i>of structural blacksmithing,</i>

33:37.349 --> 33:39.768
<i>but I don't like</i>
<i>that decorative curl.</i>

33:39.768 --> 33:41.978
<i>I got kind of a bad</i>
<i>feeling about it.</i>

33:41.978 --> 33:44.105
<i>It's very easy if you're</i>
<i>just at a bad angle</i>

33:44.105 --> 33:45.899
<i>to ruin the whole thing,</i>

33:45.899 --> 33:48.109
so you got to be real
delicate, real careful,

33:48.109 --> 33:50.946
<i>and just make sure</i>
<i>you don't screw it up or--</i>

33:50.946 --> 33:52.530
<i>when you're this far in.</i>

33:52.530 --> 33:55.158
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:55.158 --> 33:57.452
<i>- Well, I made it to day three.</i>

33:57.452 --> 33:59.996
All right, I'm gonna
put my hot cuts in.

33:59.996 --> 34:01.873
And once I get those
split...

34:01.873 --> 34:03.959
My goal for today
is to get both the blades

34:03.959 --> 34:06.711
<i>heat-treated</i>
<i>doing a differential heat.</i>

34:06.711 --> 34:09.214
<i>Since I'm only trying to quench</i>
<i>a part of the blade,</i>

34:09.214 --> 34:12.050
<i>it gives me the ability</i>
<i>to harden up the edge</i>

34:12.050 --> 34:14.469
<i>and leave my spine much softer.</i>

34:14.469 --> 34:18.181
<i>That way it can absorb</i>
<i>the shock and not break.</i>

34:18.181 --> 34:21.017
Heat-treating will make
or break my blades, literally.

34:21.017 --> 34:23.311
[bleep].

34:23.311 --> 34:25.438
Oh, for the love
of [bleep].

34:25.438 --> 34:26.982
[bleep].

34:26.982 --> 34:30.277
[bleep]. Yeah there's a warp.

34:30.277 --> 34:32.696
The blade itself
entirely is a waste.

34:32.696 --> 34:34.155
[groans]

34:36.199 --> 34:39.077
This is why we did two.

34:39.077 --> 34:41.621
<i>Wow, I am behind</i>
<i>the eight ball on this one.</i>

34:41.621 --> 34:44.708
<i>On the second blade I'll stick</i>
<i>with a normal heat-treat,</i>

34:44.708 --> 34:47.877
<i>but even then accidents</i>
<i>can pop up</i>

34:47.877 --> 34:49.337
and ruin your day.

34:49.337 --> 34:50.922
[metal clanging]

34:50.922 --> 34:52.841
Ooh, she sounds good.

34:52.841 --> 34:54.676
<i>It looked to be</i>
<i>in pretty good shape.</i>

34:54.676 --> 34:56.886
She's hard.

34:56.886 --> 34:58.888
<i>- So it's day five.</i>

34:58.888 --> 35:00.307
<i>The handle's big</i>
<i>and a little weird-shaped,</i>

35:00.307 --> 35:02.017
<i>but it's not hard to make,</i>

35:02.017 --> 35:03.351
<i>so I think I can handle</i>
<i>that just fine.</i>

35:03.351 --> 35:05.854
I'm heating this beeswax.

35:05.854 --> 35:10.400
The excess is gonna soak
into the wood and seal it.

35:10.400 --> 35:12.611
<i>All I got left to do today</i>
<i>is finish work,</i>

35:12.611 --> 35:14.529
<i>and this thing'll</i>
<i>be ready to test.</i>

35:14.529 --> 35:16.239
I know Tim's good.

35:16.239 --> 35:17.949
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>exactly what he's got,</i>

35:17.949 --> 35:19.576
<i>but I think my weapon's</i>
<i>gonna beat his.</i>

35:19.576 --> 35:24.789
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:24.789 --> 35:28.293
<i>- So today I'll be finishing</i>
<i>those hooks up.</i>

35:28.293 --> 35:33.381
<i>My only concern with the hook</i>
<i>is under extreme duress</i>

35:33.381 --> 35:35.258
if you're hitting
something really hard,

35:35.258 --> 35:38.511
you could end up snapping
that off just from vibration.

35:38.511 --> 35:41.514
<i>I'll get my guard</i>
<i>completely done tonight</i>

35:41.514 --> 35:44.684
<i>and start working on my hilt.</i>

35:44.684 --> 35:46.561
<i>Maybe when it's</i>
<i>all said and done,</i>

35:46.561 --> 35:49.939
<i>I'm gonna like this grip</i>
<i>and fall in love</i>

35:49.939 --> 35:52.359
<i>with it like I did the blade.</i>

35:52.359 --> 35:55.570
<i>I wish she'd balance just</i>
<i>a little bit further back,</i>

35:55.570 --> 35:58.615
<i>but she's definitely</i>
<i>a $10,000 weapon.</i>

36:00.784 --> 36:03.995
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:03.995 --> 36:05.997
- Bladesmiths, welcome back
to the Forge.

36:05.997 --> 36:07.582
You've had five days
at your home forge

36:07.582 --> 36:09.042
to work on your kelewangs.

36:09.042 --> 36:11.002
Hunter, how did it go?

36:11.002 --> 36:13.672
- I had a lot of trouble
in round one with the San Mai,

36:13.672 --> 36:15.548
<i>and just kind of to prove to</i>
<i>myself that I could handle it,</i>

36:15.548 --> 36:17.842
<i>I decided to do a five-layer</i>

36:17.842 --> 36:19.719
<i>Go Mai construction for mine;</i>
<i>I'm pretty happy with it.</i>

36:19.719 --> 36:23.264
- Tim, how'd it go for you?
- It went smoothly,

36:23.264 --> 36:25.225
<i>5160 spring steel,</i>

36:25.225 --> 36:27.519
<i>marine bearing red bronze</i>
<i>for the guard,</i>

36:27.519 --> 36:30.647
<i>and then elk antler</i>
<i>and cherry wood.</i>

36:30.647 --> 36:32.190
- All right, gents, your blades

36:32.190 --> 36:33.900
will now be tested
in three tests.

36:33.900 --> 36:37.237
Up first, the kill test. Doug?

36:37.237 --> 36:39.030
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:39.030 --> 36:41.366
- Bladesmiths, to see
what kind of lethal damage

36:41.366 --> 36:43.368
your kelewang will do,

36:43.368 --> 36:45.453
I will take your kelewang
and deliver slashes and thrusts

36:45.453 --> 36:47.163
on these ballistics dummies.

36:47.163 --> 36:48.998
Hunter, you're up first.
You ready?

36:48.998 --> 36:51.584
- Ready as I'm gonna get.
My blade's very sharp.

36:51.584 --> 36:54.003
I cut through probably
half a case of water bottles,

36:54.003 --> 36:56.089
took no edge deformation,
and it's sharp,

36:56.089 --> 36:57.632
so I just got to hope it's good
enough for the dummies.

36:57.632 --> 37:00.427
- While my arm is healed enough
to wield a knife

37:00.427 --> 37:02.554
on the ratchet strap slash,

37:02.554 --> 37:05.014
my arm is still healing,
so bladesmiths,

37:05.014 --> 37:07.642
please welcome RJ Marcaida.

37:07.642 --> 37:09.811
He will have the pleasure
of wielding your weapon.

37:09.811 --> 37:16.776
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:20.488 --> 37:27.412
♪ ♪

37:35.128 --> 37:37.589
- All right, Hunter, let's talk
about your kelewang right here.

37:37.589 --> 37:39.966
Your edge over here is sharp.

37:39.966 --> 37:42.677
It glides through
and lacerates.

37:42.677 --> 37:45.764
Your weapon, when slashing,
broke some ribs.

37:45.764 --> 37:48.349
Your kelewang, sir, will kill.

37:48.349 --> 37:50.518
- Thank you.
- All right, Tim, you ready?

37:50.518 --> 37:52.145
- As I'll ever be.

37:52.145 --> 37:53.813
<i>Hunter got</i>
<i>really good feedback.</i>

37:53.813 --> 37:55.940
<i>That first slice went in deep,</i>

37:55.940 --> 37:59.360
so he's got one mother
of an edge on that thing.

37:59.360 --> 38:01.988
I hope mine does that well.

38:01.988 --> 38:08.912
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:19.172 --> 38:20.590
- All right, Tim, the first
thing I noticed

38:20.590 --> 38:22.342
about it is your handle.

38:22.342 --> 38:23.718
The minute you grab onto it,

38:23.718 --> 38:25.637
it's ovoid enough
to let us know

38:25.637 --> 38:27.722
and index where the edge is.

38:27.722 --> 38:30.809
You have a tip
that's also very sharp

38:30.809 --> 38:33.228
and pointed that
when it penetrated,

38:33.228 --> 38:35.563
not only did it penetrate,
it broke some ribs also.

38:35.563 --> 38:38.900
Your kelewang will kill.

38:38.900 --> 38:41.736
- Thank you.
- Next up, the strength test.

38:41.736 --> 38:43.196
- Bladesmiths, we've taken
these parts

38:43.196 --> 38:45.365
from a buffalo plough,

38:45.365 --> 38:46.741
and to test the strength and
durability of your kelewangs,

38:46.741 --> 38:48.993
I am gonna chop into them.
Remember,

38:48.993 --> 38:51.162
this test is all about
what they do to your kelewang

38:51.162 --> 38:53.248
and not what your
kelewangs do to them.

38:53.248 --> 38:54.874
Hunter, you're up first.
You ready?

38:54.874 --> 38:56.459
- I'm ready as I'm gonna get.

38:56.459 --> 38:58.002
<i>I'm really nervous.</i>
<i>My sword's lean.</i>

38:58.002 --> 39:00.213
<i>It's pretty narrow.</i>

39:00.213 --> 39:01.631
This seems like it's gonna be
a lot more brutal on the blades

39:01.631 --> 39:02.924
than what I was expecting.

39:06.594 --> 39:11.808
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:11.808 --> 39:15.687
[metal clanging]

39:15.687 --> 39:18.398
[bleep].

39:18.398 --> 39:19.983
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:19.983 --> 39:22.235
[sighs]

39:22.235 --> 39:24.279
- Well, Hunter,
your blade broke.

39:24.279 --> 39:28.741
The main issue was that at
the intersection of the blade

39:28.741 --> 39:31.870
<i>and this decorative curl,</i>

39:31.870 --> 39:34.289
<i>there was a saw cut</i>
<i>that came in.</i>

39:34.289 --> 39:37.250
It's a sharp notch, and we call
those stress risers.

39:37.250 --> 39:39.252
They're a place where
something is gonna break.

39:39.252 --> 39:41.504
The way you protect
against that problem

39:41.504 --> 39:43.214
is you round the bottom
of that notch,

39:43.214 --> 39:46.259
and it tends to dissipate
the energy better.

39:46.259 --> 39:48.761
- Hunter, your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure

39:48.761 --> 39:51.222
and can no longer
continue with testing.

39:51.222 --> 39:53.892
However, you're not out
of this competition yet.

39:53.892 --> 39:57.103
Tim, your blade also
must survive at least five

39:57.103 --> 39:59.272
whacks in order for you
to move forward.

39:59.272 --> 40:01.441
<i>- Hunter's blade snapped.</i>

40:01.441 --> 40:05.486
<i>Now I'm even more nervous about</i>
<i>what's gonna happen to mine.</i>

40:05.486 --> 40:07.864
<i>Maybe mine'll snap as well.</i>

40:07.864 --> 40:11.242
<i>All I can think of is if my</i>
<i>blade passes</i>

40:11.242 --> 40:14.871
the strength test,
then I win.

40:35.725 --> 40:37.352
- Well, Tim, it held up.

40:37.352 --> 40:39.187
Can't see any evidence

40:39.187 --> 40:40.647
of the activity
on the edge of this blade.

40:40.647 --> 40:42.565
It's still razor-sharp.

40:42.565 --> 40:44.275
I really enjoyed swinging it.
Nice job.

40:44.275 --> 40:45.818
- Thank you so much.

40:45.818 --> 40:47.779
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:47.779 --> 40:50.615
- Hunter, your blade suffered
a catastrophic failure.

40:50.615 --> 40:54.661
For that reason I have
to dismiss you from the Forge.

40:54.661 --> 40:56.788
<i>- I'm feeling pretty</i>
<i>disappointed. I don't know.</i>

40:56.788 --> 40:58.247
<i>I just thought it was gonna be</i>
<i>more solid than that.</i>

40:58.247 --> 41:00.166
If I could start over again,

41:00.166 --> 41:02.126
I'd make the blade a little
wider, a little thicker,

41:02.126 --> 41:04.128
and just make sure it didn't
have a stress point in it.

41:04.128 --> 41:05.797
I still want to go full-time.

41:05.797 --> 41:08.424
<i>I've definitely learned a lot.</i>

41:08.424 --> 41:11.761
<i>Every blade that I make from</i>
<i>now on is gonna be better.</i>

41:11.761 --> 41:14.263
- Well, Tim, all your hard work
paid off.

41:14.263 --> 41:17.058
You turned in a kelewang that's
deadly, and let's face it,

41:17.058 --> 41:21.396
looks like a $10,000 weapon
worthy of the title

41:21.396 --> 41:24.565
"Forged in Fire" champion.
Congratulations.

41:24.565 --> 41:27.318
[applause]

41:27.318 --> 41:29.529
<i>- I wanted to prove to myself</i>
<i>more than anything</i>

41:29.529 --> 41:31.739
<i>that I am at this level.</i>

41:31.739 --> 41:33.992
<i>It feels really great to be</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

41:33.992 --> 41:36.285
I can let a lot of those doubts

41:36.285 --> 41:38.663
<i>slip to the side</i>
<i>and move past them.</i>

41:38.663 --> 41:40.832
<i>Bladesmithing, it's not</i>
<i>just what I do.</i>

41:40.832 --> 41:41.749
It's who I am.

41:41.749 --> 41:48.047
<i>♪ ♪</i>
